HEADWORD: Chiasmus
<hw>Chi*as"mus</hw> <pr>(k⟦isl⟧*⟦acr⟧z"m⟦ucr⟧s)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>chiasmo`s</grk> a placing crosswise, fr.
<grk>chia`zein</grk>. See <er>Chiasm</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Rhet.)</fld>
<def>An inversion of the order of words or phrases, when repeated or
subsequently referred to in a sentence</def>; thus,⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If e'er to bless thy sons⟦br⟧
My <qex>voice</qex> or <qex>hands</qex> deny,⟦br⟧
These <qex>hands</qex> let useful skill forsake,⟦br⟧
This <qex>voice</qex> in silence die.</q>
<rj><qau>Dwight.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

